<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the synthetic demo user
    `x_[scope]_demo_agent`. This is the second of the three demo personas
    created by the case-management POC scoped application; companions are
    `x_[scope]_demo_manager` and `x_[scope]_demo_viewer`.

    Persona role (per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL Matrix and Section 0.5.5
    State-Machine Transition Map):
      This user is the MID-TIER OPERATIONAL demo persona and is the
      MOST-REFERENCED of the three demo users. After the companion role-
      assignment row at
      ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml
      grants this user the scoped role `x_[scope]_case_agent`, this user
      gets:
        - x_[scope]_case        Create + Read Assigned-only +
                                Write Assigned-only; NO Delete
        - x_[scope]_case_task   Create + Read Assigned-only +
                                Write Assigned-only; NO Delete
        - x_[scope]_case_party  Create + Read Assigned-only +
                                Write Assigned-only; NO Delete
      "Assigned only" is defined per the AAP as
        assigned_agent = current user
          OR
        assigned_group contains current user
      and is encoded in the table-level ACL conditions
      (../../acl/x_[scope]_case_*_agent_assigned*.xml). Field-level ACLs
      on `assigned_group` (manager-only write) and `assigned_agent`
      (manager + assigned-agent write) further restrict reassignment
      operations.

      Operational role (per the seed-script's case table):
        This user is the `assigned_agent` on demo cases 03, 04, 05, 06
        (General Inquiry: In Progress / Pending / Resolved / Closed) and
        on demo cases 08, 09, 10 (Complaint: In Progress / Resolved /
        Closed) — i.e., on every demo case that has progressed past Open.
        This user is also the `assigned_to` on every one of the 8 demo
        tasks. The pattern is intentional: the demo agent is the primary
        case worker; the demo manager approves / closes; the demo viewer
        observes. This separation reinforces the operational personas in
        the validation walkthrough.

    Validation Gate 2 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3 Workflow gate):
      The operator impersonates this user to drive a case through the
      Open -> In Progress -> Resolved transitions. The
      validate_inprogress_transition subflow
      (../../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml) plus the
      x_[scope]_validate_assigned_agent_membership business rule
      (../../business_rules/x_[scope]_validate_assigned_agent_membership.xml)
      both enforce that the `assigned_agent` is a member of the
      `assigned_group` — so this user MUST be a member of the demo group
      `x_[scope]_demo_team`. That membership is established by the
      separate sys_user_grmember row in
      ../groups/sys_user_group_x_[scope]_demo_team.xml; it is NOT encoded
      on this user record (no group-membership field exists on sys_user).
      If the demo agent is NOT in the demo group, every demo case in
      In Progress or beyond will fail validation on re-save and Gate 2
      fails.

      The Resolved -> Closed transition is the ONLY transition this user
      cannot perform; that requires the x_[scope]_case_manager role.
      Attempting Resolved -> Closed while impersonating this user MUST
      surface the blocking error per the
      validate_closed_transition subflow
      (../../flows/sub_flows/validate_closed_transition.xml).

    Validation Gate 3 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3 ACLs gate):
      The operator impersonates this user to verify the gate's pass row
      "case_agent cannot access unassigned cases." If this user can
      read or write a case where neither
        assigned_agent = current user
      nor
        assigned_group contains current user
      holds, Gate 3 fails. The "Assigned only" condition is enforced at
      the ACL layer (../../acl/x_[scope]_case_*_agent_assigned*.xml); no
      client-side or business-rule guard is required to "deny" access.

    Validation Gate 4 dependency (AAP Section 0.7.3 Portal-submission
    gate):
      A case submitted via the unauthenticated portal lands in Draft
      status with NO assigned_group / assigned_agent. The demo manager
      assigns the case to the demo team and to this demo agent. The
      operator then impersonates this user to verify the case is now
      visible to the agent and that the Open -> In Progress transition
      succeeds. Gate 4 passes only if the assignment cascade works.

    Why this user record lives in the SCOPED Update Set even though
    `sys_user` is a global OOB table (per the agent prompt and AAP
    Section 0.7.2 scope-namespace exclusivity):
      The scoped Update Set's deliverable is fully self-contained: the
      reviewer must be able to install the Update Set on a fresh PDI and
      immediately exercise all seven validation gates. The three demo
      personas (manager, agent, viewer) are required by Gate 2 (workflow:
      every transition demonstration), Gate 3 (ACL role-based access),
      and Gate 4 (portal submission as an unauthenticated requester
      routed to a queue visible to this demo agent). Tracking the demo
      personas inside the scoped Update Set ensures they import together
      with the rest of the application; the scope binding via
      <sys_scope> and <sys_package> source attribute groups them with
      the scoped app even though their parent table (sys_user) is global.
      No global-scope WRITES are performed: only INSERTS into sys_user
      (a data table) — the OOB sys_user dictionary, ACLs, and form
      layouts are never modified.

    Why this user IS a member of the demo group `x_[scope]_demo_team`
    (per the agent prompt key insight #7):
      Of the three demo users, ONLY the demo agent is added to the demo
      group. The agent's read/write privileges are gated by "Assigned
      only" — i.e., the agent can only see cases where
        assigned_agent = current user
          OR
        assigned_group contains current user.
      Demo cases that are assigned to the demo team (via assigned_group)
      but not specifically to this user (assigned_agent is null or set to
      a different agent) MUST still be visible to this user via the
      group-membership branch of the "Assigned only" condition. The
      group membership is therefore essential — it is what proves the
      "OR assigned_group contains current user" branch of the ACL
      condition is honored. The membership is established by a separate
      sys_user_grmember row in
      ../groups/sys_user_group_x_[scope]_demo_team.xml; that file
      resolves THIS user by <user_name> = "x_[scope]_demo_agent" and the
      demo group by <name> = "x_[scope]_demo_team".

    Why this user IS used as `assigned_agent` on cases 03-06 and 08-10
    AND `assigned_to` on every one of the 8 demo tasks (per the agent
    prompt and the seed-script's case table):
      The demo agent's operational role is to BE the case worker, and
      the seed data must demonstrate every case status with a populated
      `assigned_agent`. Cases 01 (Draft) and 02 (Open) have no
      assigned_agent (Draft has no assigned_group either; Open has only
      assigned_group set). Cases 03 onward (In Progress, Pending,
      Resolved, Closed) MUST have an assigned_agent — and that
      assigned_agent MUST be a member of assigned_group, which forces
      the demo agent to be the populated value (since the demo agent is
      the only member of the demo group). Cases 07 (Open Complaint) is
      the Complaint-type analog of case 02: assigned_group set, no
      assigned_agent yet. Cases 08, 09, 10 are the In Progress,
      Resolved, Closed Complaints; all have this demo agent as
      assigned_agent. Tasks: every one of the 8 demo tasks has this
      user as assigned_to, since the agent is the case worker and the
      tasks are children of the in-flight cases.

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the
    agent prompt's eight authoring rules):

      Rule 1 — No PII:
        first_name = "Demo" (literal, not a real first name — no John,
                     Jane, Maria, etc.)
        last_name  = "Agent" (the role title as a synthetic surname —
                     unmistakably non-real; no real person's last name
                     would be "Agent")
        email      = "demo-agent@example.invalid" (the .invalid TLD is
                     reserved by RFC 2606 / BCP 32; never resolves to a
                     real domain — guarantees no accidental email leak)
        NO phone, NO mobile_phone, NO home_phone, NO business_phone,
        NO address fields, NO birthdate, NO SSN, NO photo,
        NO realistic full names, NO realistic email addresses.

      Rule 2 — No hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids:
        The user's OWN <sys_id> below is the record's primary key, which
        is acceptable per the AAP rule (it is NOT a reference to any
        other record). It is a deterministic 32-character lowercase hex
        value (MD5 of the canonical user_name "x_[scope]_demo_agent" =
        0ca8070bf940abded1aaa84ab389087f) so the Update Set engine
        resolves the same sys_id on every PDI import. This makes the
        downstream cross-references — group membership, role assignment,
        the seven `assigned_agent` references, all eight `assigned_to`
        references, and any Person-type party `person` references —
        idempotent and re-importable on a fresh PDI without sys_id
        collision.
        The <sys_scope> and <sys_package> reference fields resolve by
        display_value/source attributes against the scoped application's
        sys_scope record (../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml whose
        <source> field equals "x_[scope]") — NOT by hardcoded sys_id
        literals.
        NO <manager>, <department>, <location>, <company> reference
        fields are populated, so no other reference-resolution concerns
        arise.

      Rule 3 — No password:
        The <user_password/> element is empty (self-closing). A populated
        password (even hashed) in an Update Set XML would be an obvious
        credential leak risk. Demo users are signed in via the OOB
        `admin` impersonation feature in the PDI UI; they do NOT need a
        set password. To exercise this user's privileges in a fresh PDI,
        an operator with the `admin` role uses Settings -> Impersonate
        User -> select "Demo Agent" (display name).

      Rule 4 — Scope binding:
        <sys_scope> binds this user record to the scoped application
        whose sys_scope.source is `x_[scope]` (defined in
        ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml). The display_value attribute
        is "Case Management" (matching the sys_app's short_description /
        the human-readable name of the application). The <sys_package>
        follows the same pattern with the source attribute pointing at
        the scope source name. This matches the convention used by
        every other scoped artifact in the Update Set (roles, ACLs,
        dictionary entries, choices, sibling demo user records) so the
        Update Set engine groups them all under the same scope at
        import time.

      Rule 5 — Idempotency anchor:
        The user's idempotent key is <user_name> = "x_[scope]_demo_agent".
        The companion seed script ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js
        ensureUser() helper queries sys_user by user_name BEFORE
        inserting; the action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute on the inner
        <sys_user> element ensures the same behavior at Update Set
        import time. This <user_name> value MUST EXACTLY match every
        downstream reference:
          - ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js  (DEMO.USERS.AGENT constant)
          - ../groups/sys_user_group_x_[scope]_demo_team.xml  (the
            group's sys_user_grmember row resolves THIS user by
            user_name lookup)
          - ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent
            .xml  (grants the x_[scope]_case_agent role; resolves THIS
            user by user_name lookup)
          - ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_03.xml through demo_06.xml and
            demo_08.xml through demo_10.xml  (assigned_agent field
            resolves THIS user by user_name lookup; 7 cases total)
          - ../tasks/x_[scope]_case_task_demo_*.xml  (assigned_to field
            resolves THIS user by user_name lookup; 8 tasks total)
          - ../parties/x_[scope]_case_party_demo_*.xml  (person field on
            Person-type parties for case 04 Witness and case 09 Witness
            resolves THIS user by user_name lookup)

      Rule 6 — No production data:
        No real first names, last names, email addresses, phone numbers,
        addresses, or any other personally identifiable information. The
        synthetic placeholder values (Demo, Agent, demo-agent@example
        .invalid) are unmistakably non-real.

      Rule 7 — Minimum field set:
        ONLY the minimum content fields required by the AAP template are
        populated: active, email, first_name, last_name, user_name,
        user_password (empty). All additional sys_user columns (manager,
        department, phone, mobile_phone, home_phone, business_phone,
        title, location, company, photo, time_zone, date_format,
        introduction, source, u_*) are auto-defaulted by the platform on
        first import. This keeps the file small, avoids dependencies on
        other global tables (cmn_department, cmn_location, core_company),
        and makes the record resilient to ServiceNow release-version
        drift across Yokohama / Zurich / Australia.

      Rule 8 — Scoped Update Set XML conventions:
        Root element: <record_update table="sys_user">
        Inner element: <sys_user action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE"> for
        idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1 round-trip-
        verification.
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Boolean values lowercase: <active>true</active>.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching the sibling demo-user
        records at sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_manager.xml and
        sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_viewer.xml, the role records in
        ../../roles/, and every other XML in the scoped Update Set).

    Cross-dependencies (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This user IS REFERENCED BY (these files resolve THIS user by
      <user_name> = "x_[scope]_demo_agent", NOT by sys_id literal):
        - ../groups/sys_user_group_x_[scope]_demo_team.xml
            adds this user as a member of the demo group via the
            sys_user_grmember row (the membership is the prerequisite
            for the "OR assigned_group contains current user" branch of
            the "Assigned only" ACL condition)
        - ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml
            grants this user the x_[scope]_case_agent role
        - ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_03.xml  (In Progress, General
          Inquiry — assigned_agent = this user)
        - ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_04.xml  (Pending, General
          Inquiry — assigned_agent = this user)
        - ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_05.xml  (Resolved, General
          Inquiry — assigned_agent = this user)
        - ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_06.xml  (Closed, General Inquiry
          — assigned_agent = this user)
        - ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_08.xml  (In Progress, Complaint
          — assigned_agent = this user)
        - ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_09.xml  (Resolved, Complaint —
          assigned_agent = this user)
        - ../cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_10.xml  (Closed, Complaint —
          assigned_agent = this user)
        - all 8 demo task records under
          ../tasks/x_[scope]_case_task_demo_*.xml  (assigned_to = this
          user on every demo task)
        - Person-type demo party records under
          ../parties/x_[scope]_case_party_demo_*.xml  (some use this
          user as the `person` reference per the seed-script's party
          table — case 04 Witness party and case 09 Witness party in
          the canonical seed list)
        - ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js  (the DEMO.USERS.AGENT
          constant equals this user_name)

      This user IS NOT referenced by:
        - cases 01 (Draft), 02 (Open), or 07 (Open Complaint) as
          assigned_agent — those cases either have no assignment yet
          (Draft) or have only assigned_group set (Open / Open
          Complaint), per the prompt's transition rules

      Update Set ordering (per AAP Section 0.5.2):
        - This record MUST be loaded AFTER the scope/app records under
          ../../app/ (since <sys_scope>/<sys_package> reference the
          scope's source).
        - This record MUST be loaded BEFORE:
            * the demo group's sys_user_grmember membership row under
              ../groups/  (which adds THIS user as a member by user_name
              lookup)
            * the role assignment at ../role_assignments/
              sys_user_has_role_x_[scope]_demo_agent.xml  (resolves
              <user> by user_name lookup — needs this user to exist)
            * cases 03-06 and 08-10 under ../cases/  (assigned_agent
              field resolves by user_name lookup)
            * all 8 demo task records under ../tasks/  (assigned_to
              field resolves by user_name lookup)
            * the Person-type demo party records under ../parties/
              that use this user as the `person` reference (cases 04
              and 09 Witness parties)

    Cascade-impact note (per the agent prompt key insight #6):
      This is the MOST-REFERENCED of the three demo users — referenced
      by 7 cases, 8 tasks, multiple parties, the demo group, the role
      assignment, and the seed script. If this record fails to load
      during Update Set commit (e.g., due to a malformed XML, an
      unresolvable scope, or a duplicate user_name collision on the
      target PDI), every one of those 17+ downstream records will fail
      to resolve their cross-reference and the Update Set commit will
      partially fail. Validation Gate 7 (Update Set integrity) will
      block delivery. This file must therefore be perfectly valid on
      every import.

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Section 0.8.1:
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesConfig.java
        Holds `application.roles` as a List<String> bound from external
        configuration via @ListValue("application.roles"). Semantic
        anchor only: ArkCase's role-name list pattern (where role names
        like "ROLE_ARKCASE_CASE_AGENT" were held as plain strings) is
        replaced in the target by named scoped roles. This demo user is
        the principal that gets granted the x_[scope]_case_agent role
        via the separate role-assignment record.
      - ArkCase's underlying `acm_user` table (defined by AcmUser.java,
        LDAP/AD-backed in production) is NOT replicated; the ServiceNow
        target uses fully synthetic in-platform users on the OOB
        sys_user table.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - The XML well-formedness check (xmllint with no-output flag)
        returns zero errors.
      - No-PII grep returns zero matches against (john|jane|smith|doe|
        mary|maria|@gmail|@yahoo|@outlook|@hotmail|\.com|\.org|\.net).
      - No-extra-fields grep returns zero matches against (manager|
        department|phone|mobile_phone|home_phone|business_phone|title|
        location|company|photo|introduction|date_format|time_zone|
        source). Note: this validation tests for those XML element
        tags as sys_user columns — not for those words appearing in
        comments or attribute values. The role/group/membership
        relationships described in this comment are handled by separate
        record files; they are not encoded as sys_user columns here.
      - Empty-password grep returns zero matches against a populated
        user_password element of the form open-tag CHARS close-tag.
      - The user_name value matches downstream references exactly.
-->
<record_update table="sys_user">
    <sys_user action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <email>demo-agent@example.invalid</email>
        <first_name>Demo</first_name>
        <last_name>Agent</last_name>
        <sys_class_name>sys_user</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_id>0ca8070bf940abded1aaa84ab389087f</sys_id>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">x_[scope]</sys_package>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_user_x_[scope]_demo_agent</sys_update_name>
        <user_name>x_[scope]_demo_agent</user_name>
        <user_password/>
    </sys_user>
</record_update>
